20_0	0.50440913	WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, in a historic ruling affecting the constitutional balance of power at the heart of the American political system, struck down legislation Thursday that permits the president to veto specific provisions of spending and tax bills.
20_1	0.31061385	The court's 6-3 decision against the practice, known as the ``line-item veto,'' restores the historic balance between the legislative and executive branches, removing from the president's political arsenal a weapon that Congress provided in 1996 and that President Clinton used 82 times last year.
20_2	0.18936753	The Supreme Court, especially sensitive to the separation of powers because of its own institutional role, took the unusual step of noting it did ``not lightly'' reach its conclusion.
20_3	0.35560801	Justice John Paul Stevens, writing for the majority, said the issue was of ``profound importance''.
20_4	0.43149569	The court, Stevens wrote, ``has concluded that its duty is clear,'' and the line-item veto is ``not authorized by the Constitution''.
20_5	0.21486608	Though the line-item veto was provided to a Democratic president by a Republican Congress, the ability to strike out individual provisions of bills is a prerogative given to 43 of the nation's governors, sought 130 years ago by President Ulysses S.
20_6	0.063465901	Grant and desired by every modern president since Harry Truman.
